<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Shell flattened to globose-heliciform. Last whorl rounded to angular, less distorted, and often with peripheral keel; whorls regularly to rapidly expanded. Apertural dentition varied, ranging from only one parietal lamella to additional dentition: upper palatal, palatal, basal, columellar and supracolumellar lamellae. Genitalia with short to long penis, sometimes with penial appendix and penial sheath covering entire penis length. Penial hooks present and vaginal hook absent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
This genus was recently revised in both shell and genital diagnostic characters, and the intrageneric relationship was discussed (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.401.7075" author="Siriboon, T" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="45 - 107" refId="B76" refString="Siriboon, T, Sutcharit, C, Naggs, F, Rowson, B, Panha, S, 2014a. Revision of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon Pfeiffer, 1856, with description of twelve new species (Pulmonata, Streptaxidae). ZooKeys 401: 45 - 107, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.401.7075" title="Revision of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon Pfeiffer, 1856, with description of twelve new species (Pulmonata, Streptaxidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.401.7075" volume="401" year="2014 a">Siriboon et al. 2014a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2020.1783384" author="Siriboon, T" journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="720 - 738" refId="B78" refString="Siriboon, T, Naggs, F, Wade, CM, Jeratthitikul, E, Tongkerd, P, Jirapatrasilp, P, Panha, S, Sutcharit, C, 2020. Phylogenetic relationships of the carnivorous terrestrial snail family Streptaxidae (Stylommatophora: Achatinina) in Thailand and surrounding areas of Southeast Asia. Systematics and Biodiversity 18 (7): 720 - 738, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2020.1783384" title="Phylogenetic relationships of the carnivorous terrestrial snail family Streptaxidae (Stylommatophora: Achatinina) in Thailand and surrounding areas of Southeast Asia." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2020.1783384" volume="18" year="2020">2020</bibRefCitation>
). At present, the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pfeiffer" authorityYear="1856" class="Gastropoda" family="Streptaxidae" genus="Discartemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Discartemon" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Discartemon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises thirty recognized species, including a new species described herein (
<bibRefCitation author="Sutcharit, C" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" refId="B83" refString="Sutcharit, C, Lin, A, Panha, S, 2020. Two new species of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon from Thailand and Myanmar (Eupulmonata: Streptaxidae). The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology (Supplement No. 35): 149-155." title="Two new species of the carnivorous snail genus Discartemon from Thailand and Myanmar (Eupulmonata: Streptaxidae). The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology (Supplement No. 35): 149 - 155." year="2020">Sutcharit et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
